      <h2>Shared Page — Risk Disclosures (GL9SUSD + GL9XUSD)</h2>

      <h3>GODLEVEL9 Stablecoin Risk Disclosures</h3>
      <p><b>Applies to GL9SUSD (Septillion Series) and GL9XUSD (Sextillion Series)</b></p>
      <p>
        Stablecoins are designed for stability, but no system is risk-free. This page explains the key risks in plain language.
      </p>
      <p><b>Not financial advice.</b> Users should evaluate risks, local laws, and their own circumstances before using any token.</p>

      <h3>1) Redemption & Liquidity Risk</h3>
      <p>Even with reserve backing, redemption can face delays due to:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>banking hours and settlement cutoffs</li>
        <li>elevated redemption demand (“run” conditions)</li>
        <li>compliance reviews</li>
        <li>operational outages</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Redemption timelines and eligibility rules are defined in the Redemption Policy.</p>

      <h3>2) Custody / Bank Risk</h3>
      <p>Reserves depend on third-party financial institutions:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>a bank or custodian may restrict access</li>
        <li>institutions can fail or face regulatory action</li>
        <li>payment rails can experience outages</li>
      </ul>
      <p>These events may temporarily impact redemption speed.</p>

      <h3>3) Regulatory & Legal Risk</h3>
      <p>Stablecoin rules vary by jurisdiction and can change.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>certain countries may restrict stablecoin use</li>
        <li>exchanges may delist due to compliance requirements</li>
        <li>redemption availability may be limited in restricted jurisdictions</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Users are responsible for complying with local laws.</p>

      <h3>4) Compliance Risk (KYC/AML/Sanctions)</h3>
      <p>Redemption and certain services may require:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>identity verification (KYC/KYB)</li>
        <li>sanctions screening</li>
        <li>transaction monitoring</li>
        <li>enhanced due diligence for high-risk cases</li>
      </ul>
      <p>This can lead to delays or refusal where prohibited activity is suspected or where legal requirements apply.</p>

      <h3>5) Market Price Deviation Risk</h3>
      <p>Even if a stablecoin targets $1, secondary market prices can deviate due to:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>liquidity conditions</li>
        <li>exchange order book depth</li>
        <li>market stress events</li>
        <li>redemption access limitations for certain users</li>
      </ul>
      <p>A temporary deviation does not necessarily mean reserves are missing, but it can occur.</p>

      <h3>6) Smart Contract & Technical Risk</h3>
      <p>On-chain tokens rely on software:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>contract vulnerabilities can be exploited</li>
        <li>integrations (bridges, wallets, exchanges) can fail</li>
        <li>chain congestion can raise fees or delay transfers</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Mitigations may include audits, cautious upgrade policies, and emergency pause functions.</p>

      <h3>7) Operational & Governance Risk</h3>
      <p>Stablecoin operations involve people and procedures:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>human error</li>
        <li>internal control failure</li>
        <li>key management incidents</li>
        <li>fraud attempts</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Mitigations include access controls, multi-approval workflows, monitoring, and incident response plans.</p>

      <h3>8) Attestation / Reporting Limitations</h3>
      <p>Attestations (if provided) are snapshots:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>they confirm reserves as of specific dates</li>
        <li>they do not eliminate all risk</li>
        <li>reporting depends on data sources and valuation methods</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Users should review the methodology and timing of reports.</p>

      <h3>9) Force Majeure & Extraordinary Events</h3>
      <p>Events outside control may affect operations:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>systemwide banking disruptions</li>
        <li>cyberattacks on critical vendors</li>
        <li>government or court orders</li>
        <li>war, sanctions expansions, or market freezes</li>
      </ul>
      <p>These events may cause delays, pauses, or restrictions.</p>

      <h3>10) No Guarantee of Universal Access</h3>
      <p>Access can vary by:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>jurisdiction</li>
        <li>exchange support</li>
        <li>wallet or platform availability</li>
        <li>compliance eligibility</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Users may not have the same redemption path in every region.</p>

      <h3>11) Series Separation Risk (GL9SUSD vs GL9XUSD)</h3>
      <p>GL9SUSD and GL9XUSD are separate series:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>each has its own reserve bucket and reporting</li>
        <li>redemption must be requested for the correct token</li>
        <li>limits or rules may differ by series (always disclosed if so)</li>
      </ul>

