      <h3>GODLEVEL9 Stablecoin Reserve Policy</h3>
      <p><b>Applies to GL9SUSD (Septillion Series) and GL9XUSD (Sextillion Series)</b></p>
      <p>
        This policy defines what reserves are, what assets qualify, how custody works,
        how reserve coverage is calculated, and how reserves are reported for both stablecoin series.
      </p>
      <p><b>Reserve Standard:</b> Each series is designed to maintain ≥ 100% reserve backing relative to circulating supply, measured on a defined reporting cadence.</p>

      <h3>1) Reserve Coverage Rule (Core Integrity)</h3>
      <p><b>Reserve Coverage Ratio = (Total Eligible Reserves) ÷ (Circulating Supply)</b></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Target: ≥ 1.00x (≥ 100%)</li>
        <li>If a buffer is used: reserves may be held at &gt; 100% to absorb operational timing and valuation changes.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Important: GL9SUSD and GL9XUSD maintain separate reserve buckets (separate accounting, and where applicable, separate custody accounts).
      </p>

      <h3>2) Eligible Reserve Assets (Permitted Backing)</h3>
      <p>Reserves are restricted to high-liquidity assets designed to protect redemption ability:</p>

      <h3>Tier 1 (Primary)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Cash held at regulated banking partners</li>
        <li>Demand deposits (cash-equivalent bank balances)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Tier 2 (Highly Liquid Government Instruments)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Short-dated U.S. Treasury bills (or close equivalents)</li>
        <li>Overnight or very short-term instruments backed by government securities (where used)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Tier 3 (Cash-Equivalent Funds) — Optional</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Government money market funds (only if they meet internal liquidity and risk standards)</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Prohibited / Not Eligible (unless explicitly disclosed and approved)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Corporate debt / junk bonds</li>
        <li>Long-duration bonds (high interest-rate sensitivity)</li>
        <li>Equity securities</li>
        <li>Illiquid assets (private equity, long-lock products)</li>
        <li>Cryptoassets as reserve backing (unless explicitly disclosed as a different product category)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If any category outside Tier 1–2 is used, it is disclosed clearly in reporting.</p>

      <h3>3) Reserve Segregation & Ownership</h3>
      <p>Reserves are held under a segregation standard:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Segregated from operating funds</li>
        <li>Tracked by series:
          <ul>
            <li>GL9SUSD Reserves are accounted for separately</li>
            <li>GL9XUSD Reserves are accounted for separately</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Internal controls ensure reserves are not used for:
          <ul>
            <li>operating expenses</li>
            <li>speculative trading</li>
            <li>unrelated lending</li>
            <li>undisclosed collateralization</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>4) Custody & Banking Partners</h3>
      <p>Reserves are held with approved custody arrangements, such as:</p>
